items.synopsis: After winning the toss and choosing to bowl, Australia bowls England out for 283 on day one at The Oval. Follow live.

title.children: Australia bowl England out after tea on day one at The Oval

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Despite Australia's mistakes in the field this morning, they'll finish day one by far the happier of the two teams. That's been a tremendous batting display in tricky conditions to be just one down at stumps. Warner was the only batter to fall for Australia, and he won't be happy about it, a poor shot to a nothing ball outside off catching his outside edge. Aside from that it's been pretty straight forward as England's bowlers failed to get the ball singing in cloudy conditions. England's first innings score of 283 came in double quick time, but having lost wickets in clumps, there could be an argument to say they wasted their chances to capitalise on starts and make a bigger score past 300. However, as has been the case throughout this series, it's very much all still to play for. And we'll be back to tell you all about it right here tomorrow. From myself Simon Smale and Jon Healy, good morning.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Stumps: Australia 1-61 (Khawaja 26, Labuschagne 2), trail by 222

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Just as Warner was looking so solid and stable, Woakes gets him for the third innings in a row! The ball didn't do much, he just angled it across the face of Warner and he's flicked to second slip, where Crawley takes a good catch diving. He goes for 24 and England have the breakthrough.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: EDGED! WARNER IS OUT!

(Getty Images)

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Anything below 300 is decent for Australia, but my word did they score them quickly and now put Australia into an awkward spot, batting in cloudy conditions with 90 minutes or so left in the day's play. The four-and-a-half dropped catches cost them dearly, to the tune of 111 runs, 80 of those from Harry Brook. But more than the runs, the drop of Brook shortly before lunch was a hammer blow momentum-wise. Now the Aussie top order has a huge job to do. If they're any more than one wicket down by stumps, that's a big win for England.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: England are all out for 283!
